the 12th Connecticut militia, then in February-March 1789 led his family from Hebron Connecticut to Berlin Vermont — up the Connecticut River with two teams of oxen, switching from wheels to runners in Brookfield. They found the log cabin he had built the previous summer crushed under three or four feet of snow."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Founded a 1300-acre farm still in family","body":"Zachariah's 1300 acres in the East Road School District of Berlin VT — at what became the southeast corner of East Road and Scott Hill Road — passed down through generations of Perrins. His son Porter, the first boy born in Berlin, built the house at Scott Hill and Airport Road in 1815 (still standing). A descendant Henry Perrin still lived in 'Perrin territory' along Scott Hill Road into the modern era."}],"slug":"zachariah-perrin-1748"},"T01387":{"id":"T01387","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"is_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1758,"month":6,"day":17,"city":"Glastonbury","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1828,"month":9,"day":11,"city":"Berlin Corners","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont"},"parents":{"father_id":"T01001","mother_id":"U00042"},"marriages":[{"children_ids":["T01391","TD0120","T01393","T01394","T01395","T01396","TD0170","TD0138","T01399"],"spouse_id":"X01832","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1779,"location_city":"Hebron","location_county":"Tolland","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_self","end_year":1828}],"sources":[{"label":"WikiTree — Mary (Talcott) Perrin","url":"https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Talcott-49"},{"label":"Clark Univ — Mary Talcott rr23/rr23_395","url":"http://aleph0.clarku.edu/~djoyce/gen/report/rr23/rr23_395.html"}],"gender":"female","tags":["vermont_migration"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_migration","related_id":"HD0233","display_label":"Settled Vermont 1789 after cousin David Newton's 1777 migration","link_text":"David Newton"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Talcott Perrin","first_name":"Mary","last_name":"Perrin","maiden_name":"Talcott","married_names":["Perrin"],"gender":"female"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM066","landmark_blurb":"Lived on the Perrin family farmstead from her arrival in Berlin in 1789 until her death in 1828."}],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM176","plot_notes":"Berlin Corner Cemetery, Berlin Corners VT — alongside Zachariah."},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Walked to Vermont with two oxen teams","body":"In February or March 1789 Mary and Zachariah moved their family from Hebron Connecticut to Berlin Vermont — traveling up the Connecticut River with two teams of oxen, then up the White River, switching from wheels to runners at Brookfield, then over a blazed trail. They arrived to find their log cabin's roof had collapsed under three to four feet of snow."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Lost firstborn daughter Mary in 1798","body":"Mary's eldest child — also named Mary, born in Hebron — died in 1798. Four months later another daughter was born and named Mary in her sister's memory. The second Mary later married Julius Yemans Dewey and was the mother of Admiral George Dewey, hero of Manila Bay 1898."}],"slug":"mary-perrin-1758"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM190","name":"Mount Rest Cemetery","city":"Saint Johns","county":"Clinton","state":"Michigan","country":"United States","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/1167/mount-rest-cemetery","hooker_connections":["TD0184","TD0185","TD0186","X02397"],"notes":"Mount Rest Cemetery, Saint Johns, Clinton County, Michigan. Hooker-tree burials: MAJ Porter Kendrick Perrin (TD0184, 1833-1903), his wife Ella M. Sessions Perrin (X02397, 1846-1926, X-prefix spouse), their son Archer M. Perrin (TD0185, 1863-1927), and infant son Paul Rex Perrin (TD0186, 1869-1869). The Perrin Vermont-to-Michigan migration concludes here."},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"TD0163","link_text":"Ira Hobart Evans","display_label":"Cousin Ira Hobart Evans won Civil War Medal of Honor","slug":"ira-evans-1844"}]}